<br>
During our discussion on Orion and NSWR launches, I did quite a bit of research into the various forms of heavy lift vehicles. To date I've been interested in ground launch concepts such as the proposed &quot;Liberty Ship&quot; and Orion because it seemed like the only way to get hundreds to thousands of tons of material into orbit. Imagine my surprise when I found that heavy lift is not the real concern! <br>
<br>
The energy requirements of interplanetary travel require nuclear engines for efficiency purposes. But lifting objects to low orbit is well within the grasp of our current technologies. LHOx and Kerosine have been shown to be &quot;good enough&quot; fuels for launch vehicles of just about any size. In fact, nuclear technology can go to much better (and cleaner) use by converting sea water into fuel. <br>
<br>
Many people have pointed to the Sea Dragon project as a viable heavy lifter. While the Sea Dragon is definitely impressive, it is far from the only game in town. In fact, there have been dozen of heavy lifters proposed including the built and flown Saturn V. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>None of them are as expensive as current launch costs</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. As an example, the Space Shuttle was built as a medium to heavy lifter that was supposed to bring launch costs down to $800 kg. Those costs are probably still achievable. The reason why the costs are still $1800 kg is due to the lack of need for heavy lifting capabilities. The Space Shuttle would have been as economical as predicted had it flown a cargo mission once per week. No such economics materialized, and NASA's attempts to force the issue resulted in the Challenger accident. <br>
<br>
It is my belief that NASA will never be able to build an affordable heavy lifter. NASA was born of politics and is to this day tied to politics. The only way to bring down launch costs is a private launch organization. Unfortunately, every launch organization to date has been regulated out of existence. Companies that have tried to circumvent regulations by launching near the equator have been shut down by locals and protesters. Apparently, no one wants a launcher in their back yard. <br>
<br>
With this in mind, it would seem that launches from sea are the most feasible. Whether they be wet launches like the Sea Dragon, or dry launches from a rig or small island is inconsequential. They simply have to be launched off of owned and regulated land.<br>
<br>
Interesting enough, the real problem is less of heavy launch and more of crew launch. Every heavy launch lifts materials and technologies that could potentially produce income for a company. Nuclear spacecraft, orbital hotels, space stations, comsats, etc. But every human lift costs significant funds in safety, training, lower G boosts, and return capabilities. Things get particularly dicey when humans wish to commute between the surface and space. Health reasons (for example) can even make such commutes a necessity!<br>
<br>
A careful study of the various forms of propulsion quickly shows that traditional rockets are not a particularly good solution for transporting people into space. Traditional rockets expend far too much fuel and hardware to be flying for simple commutes. In the end, the only craft that makes sense is an HTOL (Horizontal Takeoff and Landing) craft. <br>
<br>
I'm sure quite a few readers are currently in the process of rolling their eyes and saying, &quot;Of course HTOL makes the most sense! Too bad no one has yet built one!&quot; Which would be a perfectly valid statement. NASA is attempting to build a hypersonic HTOL craft, but their concepts simply call for too much engineering. The craft has to be rigid enough to withstand speeds of up to Mach 20 within the atmosphere! Considering that the fastest (declassified) military craft have gotten nowhere near that kind of speed, it's hard to imagine that NASA would be successful in their endeavors. Especially when we consider that their SCRAMJET craft must linger inside thicker atmosphere or it won't have enough velocity and fuel to reach LEO! <br>
<br>
The best solution I see is the use of Nuclear Thermal Engines in an air breathing configuration. Very simply, air flowing through the intakes would be cycled through an NTR engine and used as propellant. Besides the advantages of modern engineering and better shielding, the primary difference between this engine and Project Pluto, is that the engine would augment its air breathing capabilities with stored fuel whenever necessary. Thus the craft would be able to use stored fuel for takeoff maneuvers, then produce a constant climb toward LEO. Lift generated by normal flight will allow for massive energy savings and more tonnage to be carried. As the atmosphere thins, the craft will be able to achieve higher speeds with minimal hypersonic interference. Then as the atmosphere becomes too thin, fuel from storage will be dumped into the engine to augment (and eventually replace) the NiOx fuel from the atmosphere. <br>
<br>
Reentry could be accomplished in a similar manner. Since the craft will have an abundant supply of fuel inside the atmosphere, it won't need to make a sharp dive like the Space Shuttle does. In fact, a gental orbital decline will slow the plane and allow normal flight operations without any special heat shielding. No dangerous slalom maneuvers, no ionization induced communications blackouts, and no unpowered glides. The craft could easily reach the economics of today's 747 &amp; 777 craft. <br>
<br>
While this all sounds good on paper, there are several engineering challenges that must first be faced:<br>
<br>
1. A flight-capable nuclear thermal engine that does not loose any of its core. Radiation inside the exhaust may be acceptable as long as no radioisotopes are present (or only minor amounts from particles in the air).<br>
<br>
2. An airframe with lift abilities similar to commercial jets, but rigid enough to travel at supersonic speeds. (Note: It is difficult for me to know what are the maximum stresses that the airframe must face. As the air thins, the stresses are fall off and standard air speed meters may read anywhere from subsonic to mild supersonic speeds.)<br>
<br>
<br>
I'd be most interested in hearing other's thoughts on this. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=greyhavoc>Grey Havoc</A></span><br> Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/4/04 3:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> From Spacedaily.com:<br>
