Death Before Dishonour!. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=akaimbatman>AKAImBatman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/04 11:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> As I said in my original post, a vertical lifter is far too expensive a method for taking humans into space. The only way the economics of human transport will work is if the craft is nearly 100% reusable. This would tend to suggest an HTOL craft like the one I described in my original post. <br>
<br>
That being said, if your purpose is to get cargo up or down, a traditional heavy lifter craft is just the ticket. There's no need for exotic technologies for heavy lifters. The economics are already proven. <br>
<br>
In short, use the right tool for the right job. That's why humans almost always use airplanes to travel intercontinental, while ships are still used to haul the heavy cargo. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/04 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> Ships do haul bulk cargo, like oil, coal, scrap metal, grain, chemicals, containers full of manufactured 'stuff'.<br>
<br>
But airplanes also haul cargo - especially  high valued or time sensitive stuff - like perishable foods (e.g. lobster, salmon, . . . ), medicines, donated organs and blood, cut flowers, mail, packages of parts for equipment or machinery (as long as not too heavy).<br>
