Clearly there is a need for better systems.<br>
<br>
SSTO's might be more economical with Mag-launch systems, but building and operating Mag-launch could also be a technical challenge. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=akaimbatman>AKAImBatman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/04 12:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> BTW, the Delta Clipper (DC-XA) was probably a sufficient vehicle for my proposals. Had its ability to reach LEO and survive reentry been tested, it might have been an excellent craft. The real expense in most VTOL vehicles, is the disposable hardware. It's okay to dispose of hardware when the cargo is going one way, and has a real profit return. It is *not* okay to shed hardware for light lifting, where the cost of the hardware is far more than the cargo will ever return. Still, it would be best if we could build a craft that can carry actual passengers instead of a slightly larger crew. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=akaimbatman>AKAImBatman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/5/04 1:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> But airplanes also haul cargo - especially  high valued or time sensitive stuff - like perishable foods (e.g. lobster, salmon, . . . ), medicines, donated organs and blood, cut flowers, mail, packages of parts for equipment or machinery (as long as not too heavy).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Correct. I didn't say it in so many words, but that is how I envisioned the HTOL craft to be used. Anything that you'd carry on a plane today would be the type of thing you'd carry on these light lifters. It's silly to send shipments of potato chips up on a heavy booster. Right tool for the right job. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> With respect to returning to earth's surface, a craft traveling in LEO is traveling at least 17,000 mph.  The shuttle does us rockets for breaking (and Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo all used retrorockets for the same purpose) to break from orbit and start the descent.  But there is not craft yet that powers down - it requires too much fuel to thrust continuously in the upper atmosphere.  That fuel takes away from 'useful' payload mass.  Not every mission goes up almost empty.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I realize that no craft currently achieve powered flight on their way down. Currently, it's just too expensive to ship the fuel up when you can just attach some heat shielding. The HTOL craft I proposed would have plenty of fuel, however. Since air *is* fuel, it should be able to get up and down with plenty of fuel reserves in store. <br>
<br>
I'm actually surprised you haven't commented on it yet. I was expecting about 30 million reasons why it won't work, or isn't a good idea. The biggest issue I've been considering is thrust. Would NTR ramscoops generate enough thrust on their own? Would such a craft need to supplement its thrust by using some stored hydrogen? (The hydrogen would obviously have an explosive reaction to the intake oxygen. This would increase thrust substantially over thermal thrust alone.) Perhaps a pulse jet design is more in order?<br>
<br>
What I do know is this: We can build reactors light enough to fly. Project Pluto generated 35,000 pounds of thrust from 513 megawatts. That's about 68 pounds per megawatt. The Phoebus-2A reactor generated 1500MW of power. I don't know what kind of thrust it produced though. The baseline for the NERVA project was 75,000 pounds at 1100MW, which gives about the same 68 pounds per megawatt. Thus we have a baseline for NTR thrust (although the DUMBO project was an attempt to make the engines lighter and more efficient). With research into the Prometheus reactor, we may finally set new standards for how light a reactor can get.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/6/04 4:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>you haven't commented on it yet<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I presume you mean 'air breathing, nuclear direct thrust' -I just haven't gotten to that yet.  It's complicated.<br>
<br>
Concerning heavy lift/space shuttle.  One feature of the shuttle is that the SBR's are recovered and the rocket motors (SSME's) stay with the shuttle.  Only the large main fuel tank is lost.  That was an attractive feature - not throwing away very expensive rocket motors.<br>
<br>
In conventional multi-stage systems, whatever does not make ti into LEO, e.g. first and second stages of a 3 stage system, is trashed - that's very expensive.<br>
<br>
But the way, the Space Shuttle is operated is not very economical and so the cost savings of keeping the rocket motors is never fully realized.<br>
<br>
There is still the remote possibility of an SSTO, but how much of a 'heavy lift' it will provide is the key question. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gennaro@nuclearspace>Gennaro</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/6/04 8:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> These are my thoughts on the subject:<br>
<br>
The reason the space shuttle is extremely uneconomical is less of a design feature (although it matters substantially of course), above all it's a matter of the insignificant launch rate.<br>
<br>
But in order to increase launch rates there must be something worthwhile to ship. Currently there is nothing, save excuses for keeping the shuttle operational (the ISS).<br>
<br>
Any idea of space commercialization must begin with what profits can be generated <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>down on Earth</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. As far as I can see the only potential markets with any promise of potential future volume are things like platinum group metals and deuterium imports. Tourism is secondary at best and incompatible with economics of scale, beamed solar energy has no real advantage over Earth systems and is uncompetitive compared to terrestrial nuclear power. If you don't get volume demand you'll end up with a shuttle situation, no matter how fast turn-arounds your VTOL systems can achieve.<br>
For the above mentioned kinds of imports the destinations are basically three: asteroids, Mars and perhaps the Moon.<br>
<br>
Problem I: Demand for PGM's is limited. The assets on Earth suffice for the time being.<br>
<br>
Solution: We must wait for demand to increase (it has steadily over time). We should not try to mobilize private capital for space commercialization, which will only be discovered as intrinsically uncompetitive compared to any other investment option down on Earth. Rather, commercialization should be conducted as part of a state-funded space program (the planned socialist way), intended to off-set space program expenditure or even make a small profit. The goods will be sold for market values with smaller profit margins, something private enterprise would see no point in doing.<br>
<br>
Problem II: Future demand for deuterium to use in fusion reactors will be had from harvesting sea water.<br>
<br>
Solution: Same as above. Sifting through sea water in search of deuterium will still be expensive while it actually can be had as a by-product of Mars settlements.<br>
<br>
Transporting stuff through space is no problem as long as you can get fuel up. The problem is and always has been orbit to surface transits. Expendable boosters will always be too expensive, you need fully reusable systems capable of hundreds of missions and rapid turn-arounds, hence VTOVL.<br>
Such schemes typically include some jump-off point like a *real* toroidal space station or Moonbase, capable of refueling and somewhat servicing interplanetary craft as well as storing and transferring cargo between transport systems. But the infrastructure needs some way to get into place to start with, so we still need some sort of super heavy launcher to get underway (Orion anyone?).<br>
Naturally, neither in this regard can we rely on private capital to finance such a mega huge and risky undertaking providing only uncertain returns. Such infrastructure must be state-funded as well.<br>
<br>
One use for expendable rockets in interplanetary space I can envision however would be Mars-Terra transports. A mature Mars settlement could possibly produce primitive solid fuel rockets which are sent on an Earth trajectory and which upon reaching orbit release inflatable cargo dumpers to get payload down to Earth.<br>
<br>
Breakthroughs in space elevator design could be an alternative or complement to a fleet of VTOVL's.<br>
<br>
If you find the above grim prospects as far as practicality and profitability is concerned I have to agree. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->                   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gennaro@nuclearspace>Gennaro</A> at: 3/6/04 9:57 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 101<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/6/04 10:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=400.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Related Article</span><hr size=1> The shuttle is under utilized and that increases the per flight cost.  The station is going as originally planned and there are not missions to anywhere else - Moon or Mars.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>. . . various &quot;off the cuff&quot; calculations that showed that the Shuttle simply didn't have enough energy to get to orbit, therefore it would never fly. I *think* that Enterprise showed them correct, . . . <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Here's a little background on the Space Shuttle Fleet:<br>
<br>
OV-099 Challenger<br>
